sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583104
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
CsgA is a protein monomer which can aggregate to form amyloid nanowires in natural biofilms taken from E.coli K-12 MG1655. Inspired by mussels, the Mfp5 (mussel foot protein) has high adhesive properties towards wet polar surfaces. By creating a fusion protein, the adhesive properties of the mussel foot protein is combined with the formation of nanowires.
This DNA was synthesized. The design was based on the paper "Strong underwater adhesives made by self-assembling multi-protein nanofibres".[1]
1. C.Zhong, T.Gurry, A.Cheng, J.Downey, Z.Deng, C. Stultz, T.Lu, Nature Nanotechnology, 2014, 9, 858-866.
The CsgA sequence originates from the genomic DNA of E. coli K-12 MG1655 (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/949055).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
This part originates from the E.coli K-12 MG1655 genome and from mussels. The design was based on the paper "Strong underwater adhesives made by self-assembling multi-protein nanofibres".[1]
1. C.Zhong, T.Gurry, A.Cheng, J.Downey, Z.Deng, C. Stultz, T.Lu, Nature Nanotechnology, 2014, 9, 858-866.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: A mutation had to be introduced at base pair 766 to remove a PstI restriction site. The protein sequence was not changed in doing so.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583057
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Spacer in between coding sequence and suffix
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Designed as a spacer of 6 base pairs between our coding sequence and the biobrick suffix.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Non-coding and non-self-complementary codons were chosen at random.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Hairpin formation and self-complementary sequences were avoided.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583059
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Addition of a His tag at the N-terminal end of a protein of interest is goal of this basic part.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Standard DNA sequence optimized for E.coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The codon was optimized for synthesis to avoid repetetive motives of too many codons.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583013
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: CsgA missing the start codon for fusion protein
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: In order to create a fusion protein of CsgA with Mfp5 in front of it, CsgA was designed without its start codon.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This DNA was synthesized. The design was based on the paper "Strong underwater adhesives made by self-assembling multi-protein nanofibres".[1] 1. C.Zhong, T.Gurry, A.Cheng, J.Downey, Z.Deng, C. Stultz, T.Lu, Nature Nanotechnology, 2014, 9, 858-866. An illegal PstI restriction site (766) in CsgA had to be mutated (A->G) not changing the protein sequence.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: An illegal PstI restriction site (766) in CsgA had to be mutated (A->G) not changing the protein sequence.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: L-rhamnose-inducible promoter is capable of high-level recombinant protein expression in the presence of L-rhamnose, it is also tightly regulated in the absence of L-rhamnose by the addition of D-glucose.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583054
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Non-coding scar site in between RBS and gene
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: CsgC is positively involved in the extracellular aggregation of CsgA into amyloid nanowires (curli assembly) in E.coli functioning as a chaperone for CsgA.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The RBS and CsgC were synthesized from the genomic sequence of E.coli K-12 MG1655. The promoter is part of the constitutive promoter family made by John Anderson from iGEM Berkeley 2006.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We inserted non-coding scar sequences after the promoter and RBS to prevent missing initial codons during transcription/translation.
